{
  "texts": [
    "Crucially, in the {H, S, T, CNOT} gate set, for constant target error ϵ, the method of Ref.",
    "[18] does not achieve Θ(n) depth.",
    "While they do not explicitly report the depth in this gate set, this can be seen by the fact that their circuit has O(2 n) arbitrary single-qubit gates spread out over O(n) distinct layers; to convert to the discrete gate set while incurring constant overall error, each single-qubit gate must be approximately decomposed into a sequence of depth at least Ω(log(n)), yielding total depth at least Ω(n log(n)).",
    "Our state preparation method will have depth Θ(n) even in the discrete gate set, when ϵ is taken as a constant.The value of minimizing with respect to spacetime allocation is also apparent in the context of realistic hardware considerations.",
    "For example, in gate-based near-term devices without error correction, reducing the spacetime allocation (even as circuit size remains the same) amounts to reducing the time that qubits are left idling."
  ]
}